Wilma should start with:
1 SLED criminal history / rap sheet
2 Court docket from the magistrate, municipal, General Sessions, Family Court, or other court
3 Certified disposition if available
4 Solicitor or clerk confirmation for expungement route
South Carolina Legal Services explains that SLED is the state agency responsible for reports of arrests and convictions and that a SLED report may be obtained for a fee. ("https://sclegal.org/brochures/overcoming-a-criminal-record-expungement/?utm_source=chatgpt.com")
Wilma should collect:
full name and prior names;
date of birth;
county and court;
case number;
arrest date;
charge date;
original charge and final charge;
disposition;
whether it was summary court, General Sessions, Family Court, or juvenile;
whether the user was fingerprinted;
whether charges were dismissed as part of a plea;
conviction date;
sentence completion date;
probation/parole completion date;
whether fines/restitution/program fees were paid;
whether there are later convictions;
whether there are pending charges;
whether the offense involved a motor vehicle, domestic violence, violence, sex-offender registration, trafficking, firearms/weapons, DUI, injury, death, or drugs;
whether the case was connected to trafficking/coercion/exploitation.

Step 1 - Court level
Ask:

Was this in magistrate/municipal court, General Sessions, or Family Court?

If summary court check 17-22-950 first.If General Sessions check 17-1-40, diversion, YOA, drug, firearm, and conviction routes.If Family Court check juvenile 63-19-2050.
Step 2 - Disposition
Ask:

How did the case end: dismissed, nolle prossed, not guilty, acquitted, completed diversion, conditional discharge, guilty plea, conviction, youthful offender sentence, or still pending?

Pending charges usually block or delay most expungement routes.
Step 3 - If conviction, identify exact statutory route
Ask:

Was this a first offense fraudulent check, low-level magistrate/municipal conviction, third-degree domestic violence, Youthful Offender Act sentence, drug possession/PWID offense, failure to stop, old unlawful handgun possession, or trafficking-related offense?

Step 4 - Check waiting period and clean period
Ask:

Since that conviction or sentence completion, have you had any other convictions anywhere?

For YOA, failure-to-stop, and many conviction routes, later convictions can block relief.
Step 5 - Check exclusions
Ask about:
motor vehicle operation;
violent crime;
domestic violence category;
sex-offender registration;
drug trafficking/manufacturing/distribution;
felony classification;
pending charges;
dismissed charges tied to guilty pleas;
trafficking/coercion facts.
14.
Do not say eligible unless&
rules
Wilma should not say
you are eligible
unless:
For summary court non-conviction
court was magistrate/municipal;
charge was dismissed, nolle prossed, or not guilty;
no related pending charges from the same events;
dismissal was not just a preliminary-hearing dismissal;
fingerprinted/not fingerprinted status is known.
For General Sessions non-conviction
disposition was dismissal, nolle, not guilty, discharge, or acquittal;
Wilma knows whether it was part of a plea arrangement;
the proper Solicitors Office is identified.
For 22-5-910 conviction
offense penalty fits;
offense did not involve motor vehicle operation;
3-year or 5-year period has passed;
no other convictions during the period;
pending-charge rule checked;
user has not used the route before.
For YOA
user was actually sentenced under YOA;
five years have passed after completing sentence/probation/parole;
no convictions during service or five-year period;
offense is not excluded.
For drug routes
exact drug statute and offense type confirmed;
first-offense status confirmed;
waiting period confirmed;
no later convictions/pending charges checked.
For trafficking survivor route
user reports trafficking/coercion/exploitation connection;
offense category appears covered;
manual/legal review triggered.
